how limited life can be. Especially when you have a big family, which compared to this country may be a pretty big size. But all the same is a pain because, almost everything depends on everybody, and the old saying that “Sometimes you have to bite the bullet” is very true. Tough love, in a place like this is how I explain it.

After I got back from the States, they lived for a few years at Rancho Del Rey, in Brisas Del Chiriqui. At the time I thought we were one big happy family, working as a family, and despite the fact that we were none of us getting really rich, we at least could see the future. My father has always been a bit of a control freak, and is perhaps even a bit paranoid.

Even if we were not exactly cool with what my father wanted. I did not had constant arguments with my dad then. It was more of restrained, understated wrath. I felt close to him but was bothered with his overbearing and forceful grip on our brothers and sisters, and especially our mother. Bragging aside, I think I was the most difficult person you could set against him, and that is absolutely not a compliment to me, please take my word.

Me and my brother son. Panama

Even if I obeyed him, some of us resisted with our whole heart, and our mother did all in her power to make him a little more humane and friendly. To accept
